data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with LINQ when checking a condition across all items
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull for null checks
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or `CollectionAssert.IsNotEmpty` | Clear failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Semantic clarity |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(condition, "message")` | Always add a message for non-obvious checks |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify contents regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Verify contents and order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Check that a collection contains a specific item
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// All items are of a given type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// No nulls in the collection
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// No duplicates
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

**Rule of thumb:** use the most specific assertion available — it produces the most helpful failure messages and makes test intent obvious.
